{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778304706,"nonce":"2Lvs739M6P7sTWpEW3bKmB5m1dE=","title":"Reduce / eliminate pre-go-cue anticipation in trained controllers","message":"## Phenomenon\n\nThe 2026-05-09 baseline 2x2x2 matrix (efc4d68 comment ecfecc4) and follow-up MotorNet-anticipation diagnostic (`/tmp/flavor_ab_review/findings/anticipation_motornet_v3.md`) confirmed that all 40 trained replicates exhibit small but non-trivial pre-go-cue forward-velocity drift in the goal direction:\n\n- GRU cells: +5.4 to +7.6 mm in 200 ms pre-go window (1.0-1.5% of 0.5 m reach)\n- vRNN cells: +2.5 mm (0.5%)\n\nCatch-trial proportion is already at the published convention (50%, per Codol/Michaels MotorNet paper Shahbazi 2025) — we are at the literature ceiling for this single lever.\n\n## Why this matters\n\nUser-formulated soft-state-space-boundary hypothesis (currently plausible, not yet verified):\n\nThe optimization tolerates anticipation during training, suggesting the network's 'wait' state and 'move' state are not separated by a hard boundary in state space. This could globally destabilize convergence, even if anticipation magnitude per replicate is small. If true, eliminating anticipation should reduce inter-replicate trajectory variance.\n\n## Prep-duration literature context\n\nRelevant to strategy 5 below. Exact values from Michaels-group papers:\n\n- **Shahbazi et al. (2025) bioRxiv** (Savings): go-cue drawn uniformly from **100–300 ms** after trial start (50% catch trials, no go-cue). 1 s trials / 100 timesteps at 10 ms. Preparatory analysis window: 340 ms before go-cue.\n- **Shahbazi et al. (2025) — MotorNet eLife paper** (Codol, Michaels et al. 2024): go-cue fixed at **100 ms** during testing; drawn from a uniform distribution spanning the full 1 s simulation window during training. Catch trials: 50%.\n- **Kashefi et al. (2025) Nature**: biological (monkey) study — prep durations **300–500 ms** tested, with 300 ms as the canonical delay; movement window 600 ms.\n- **Michaels eLife (2020) 'when and why does motor preparation arise'**: delay period **0–800 ms** tested; 300–500 ms used in key figures.\n\nOur current `epoch_len_ranges = [[10, 11], [5, 20]]` gives 100–110 ms target-on and 50–200 ms pre-go. This is comparable to the Shahbazi 2025 bioRxiv convention (100–300 ms). Bumping to `[15, 30]` (150–300 ms) would better match the monkey prep timescale (Kashefi 2025) and the upper end of the Shahbazi range, at the cost of longer total trial length and increased BPTT memory.\n\n## Intervention strategies (logged as menu)\n\n### Loss-side\n\n1. **Pre-go-masked motor-output penalty** (NEW, just implemented via feedbax `EpochMaskedLoss` 50507a9 + rlrmp wiring efc4d68 children).\n   `λ · 𝟙[t \u003c t_go] · ‖u_t‖²` — penalizes controller force during hold/pre-go epochs only. Suppresses anticipatory motor output WITHOUT affecting null-space preparatory hidden activity. CLI: `--nn-output-pre-go \u003cweight\u003e`.\n\n2. **Pre-go-masked hidden-derivative penalty** (NEW, also implemented).\n   `λ · 𝟙[t \u003c t_go] · ‖ḣ_t‖²` — penalizes hidden-state changes during pre-go. Suppresses anticipation BUT also kills null-space preparation (caveat). CLI: `--nn-hidden-derivative-pre-go \u003cweight\u003e`.\n\n3. **Full-trajectory hidden-derivative at high weight** (literature-aligned).\n   `λ · ‖ḣ_t‖²` over the entire trajectory at weight `1e2` (Shahbazi 2025 Eq. 1). NO new code — just a flag value bump. We previously tested at `1e-3` (the matrix); never tested at the published value.\n\n### Architectural\n\n4. **Null-space confinement** (Schimel/Hennequin 2024 eLife). Architectural constraint enforcing that preparatory hidden-state changes lie in the output-readout null subspace. Highest implementation lift; deferred.\n\n### Task-side\n\n5. **Increase preparation duration** — bump `epoch_len_ranges[1]` from `[5, 20]` to `[15, 30]` (matching the 150–300 ms monkey prep timescale; see Kashefi 2025). Independent of strategies 1–4.\n\n## Decision criteria for choosing among strategies\n\nStrategies (1), (2), (3), (5) are all empirical: test whichever is cheapest first, escalate if needed. Recommend a 5-cell follow-up matrix:\n\n- `gru__jerk` (control)\n- `gru__jerk_motor_pre` (strategy 1)\n- `gru__jerk_hidden_pre` (strategy 2)\n- `gru__jerk_full_smooth_high` (strategy 3 — Shahbazi-aligned baseline)\n- `gru__jerk_long_prep` (strategy 5 — task-side fix, retrains with `epoch_len_ranges[1] = [15, 30]`)\n\nStrategy 4 (null-space confinement) is deferred separately.\n\n## Cross-references\n\n- Phase umbrella `f695729` (Stage 0 closed; this work informs subsequent stages)\n- `efc4d68` (smoothness retrain umbrella; primary tracking)\n- `c99ad9d` (training-methods coord)\n- `4d38c15` (analyses coord; will eventually motivate updates)\n- Subagent findings: `/tmp/flavor_ab_review/findings/anticipation_motornet_v3.md`, `/tmp/flavor_ab_review/findings/peak_velocity_diagnostic.md`, `/tmp/flavor_ab_review/findings/variance_matrix_results.md`","files":null}]}